{{short description| Ethically controversial aims to improve the genetic quality of the human population through selective breeding}}
{{Use dmy dates|date= May 2016}}
[[File:Eugenics congress logo.png|thumb|350px |Logo from the [[Second International Eugenics Conference]], 1921, depicting eugenics as a tree which unites a variety of different fields<ref>{{cite book |last= Currell |first= Susan |last2= Cogdell |first2= Christina |title= Popular Eugenics: National Efficiency and American Mass Culture in The 1930s |publisher= [[Ohio University Press]] |date= 2006 |page= 203 |location= Athens, Ohio |isbn= 978-0-8214-1691-4}}</ref>]]
{{Pseudomedicine sidebar|fringe}}
{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}

'''Eugenics''' ({{IPAc-en|j|uː|ˈ|dʒ|ɛ|n|ɪ|k|s}}; from [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] εὐγενής ''eugenes'' - "well-born")<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/morph?l=eugenes&la=greek#lexicon |title= εὐγενής |work= Greek Word Study Tool |publisher= Tufts University |location= Medford, Massachusetts |date= 2009 |access-date= 19 October 2017}}  Database includes entries from ''[[A Greek–English Lexicon]]'' and other English dictionaries of Ancient Greek.</ref><ref name=":0" /> is a set of beliefs and practices that aim to improve  the [[genetics |genetic]] quality of a [[human population]],<ref>{{cite web | url= http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/glossary=eugenics | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20101016010504/http://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/glossary=eugenics |archive-date= 16 October 2010 |title= Eugenics |work= Unified Medical Language System (Psychological Index Terms) |location= Bethesda, Maryland |publisher= National Library of Medicine |date= 2009<!--Earliest archive date; the "published" date given on the page was auto-generated, ever-changing, and meaningless.--> |url-status= dead |access-date= 19 October 2017}}</ref><ref name="Galton 1904">{{cite article|title= Eugenics: Its Definition, Scope, and Aims|last= Galton|first= Francis|year= 1904|journal= The American Journal of Sociology |volume= X |issue= 1 |access-date= 1 January 2020 | url= http://galton.org/essays/1900-1911/galton-1904-am-journ-soc-eugenics-scope-aims.htm}}</ref> typically by excluding people and groups judged to be inferior, and promoting those judged to be superior.<ref name="Spektorowski"/>

The concept predates the term; [[Plato]] suggested applying the principles of [[selective breeding]] to humans around 400&nbsp;BC. Early advocates of eugenics in the 19th century regarded it as a way of improving groups of people. In modern usage, the term ''eugenics'' has close ties to [[scientific racism]] and [[white supremacism]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |url= https://www.oxfordbibliographies.com/view/document/obo-9780190280024/obo-9780190280024-0029.xml|title= Eugenics – African American Studies |access-date= 2019-07-25 |website= Oxford Bibliographies}}</ref> Modern bioethicists who advocate [[new eugenics]] characterise it as a way of enhancing individual traits, regardless of group membership.

While eugenic principles have been practiced as early as [[ancient Greece]], the contemporary [[history of eugenics]] began in the early 20th century, when a popular eugenics movement emerged in the [[United Kingdom]],<ref>{{Cite journal |jstor= 25054146 |title= Eugenic Ideas, Political Interests and Policy Variance Immigration and Sterilization Policy in Britain and U.S |date= 1 January 2001 |journal= World Politics |doi= 10.1353/wp.2001.0003 |pmid= 18193564 |volume= 53 |issue= 2 |pages= 237–263|last1= Hansen |first1= Randall |last2= King |first2= Desmond }}</ref> and then spread to many countries, including the [[Eugenics in the United States|United States]], Canada,<ref>{{cite web | url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=oBYvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=TqgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6315,1778929 |title= Sterilization of Unfit Advocated – Feeble-minded Increasing at Disproportionate Rate in Canada – Case for Ungenics |work= The Montreal Gazette |volume= CLXII |issue= 272 |date= 14 November 1933 |via= News.Google.com |access-date= 19 October 2017}}</ref> and most European countries. In this period, people from across the political spectrum espoused eugenic ideas. Consequently, many countries adopted eugenic policies, intended to improve the quality of their populations' genetic stock. Such programs included both ''positive'' measures, such as encouraging individuals deemed particularly "fit" to reproduce, and ''negative'' measures, such as marriage prohibitions and [[forced sterilization]] of people deemed unfit for reproduction. Those deemed "unfit to reproduce" often included people with [[Mental disabilites |mental]] or [[physical disabilities]], people who scored in the low ranges on different [[Iq tests |IQ tests]], criminals and "deviants," and members of disfavored [[minority groups]].

The eugenics movement became associated with [[Nazi Germany]] and the [[Holocaust]] when the defense of many of the defendants at the [[Nuremberg trials]] of 1945 to 1946 attempted to justify their [[human-rights]] abuses by claiming there was little difference between the [[Nazi eugenics]] programs and the [[Eugenics in the United States |U.S. eugenics]] programs.<ref>{{cite book |title= The Oxford Handbook of the History of Eugenics |first1= Alison |last1= Bashford |first2= Philippa |last2= Levine |publisher= [[Oxford University Press]] | url= https://books.google.com/?id=g15rfXUA2i8C&pg=PA327&lpg=PA327&dq=eugenics+defense+nuremberg+trials#v=onepage&q=eugenics%20defense%20nuremberg%20trials&f=false |page= 327|isbn= 978-0199706532 |date= 2010-08-03 | access-date = 26 February 2020 | quote = Eugenics was prominent at the Nuremberg trials [...] much was made of the similarity between U.S. and German eugenics by the defense, who argued that German eugenics differed little from that practiced in the United States [...].}}</ref> In the decades following [[World War II]], with more emphasis on [[human rights]], many countries began to abandon eugenics policies, although some Western countries (the [[Compulsory sterilization#United States| United States]], [[Compulsory sterilization in Canada| Canada]], and [[Sweden]] among them) continued to carry out forced sterilizations.

Since the 1980s and 1990s, with new [[assisted reproductive technology]] procedures available, such as [[gestational surrogacy]] (available since 1985), [[preimplantation genetic diagnosis]] (available since 1989), and [[cytoplasmic transfer]] (first performed in 1996), concern has grown about the possible revival of a more potent form of eugenics after decades of promoting human rights.

A criticism of eugenics policies is that, regardless of whether ''negative'' or ''positive'' policies are used, they are susceptible to abuse because the genetic selection criteria are determined by whichever group has [[political power]] at the time.{{cn|date=February 2020}} Furthermore, many criticize ''negative eugenics'' in particular as a violation of [[basic human rights]], seen (since 1968's Proclamation of Tehran<ref>
[http://www1.umn.edu/humanrts/instree/l2ptichr.htm Proclamation of Tehran, Final Act of the International Conference on Human Rights, Teheran, 22 April to 13 May 1968, U.N. Doc. A/CONF. 32/41 at 3 (1968)], [[United Nations]],  May 1968 - "16. The protection of the family and of the child remains the concern of the international community. Parents have a basic human right to determine freely and responsibly the number and the spacing of their children [...]
</ref>) as including the [[Reproductive rights | right to reproduce]]. Another criticism is that eugenics policies eventually lead to a loss of [[genetic diversity]], thereby resulting in [[inbreeding depression]] due to a loss of genetic variation. Yet another criticism of contemporary eugenics policies is that they propose to permanently and artificially disrupt millions of years of evolution, and that attempting to create genetic lines "clean" of "disorders" can have far-reaching ancillary downstream effects in the [[genetic ecology]], including negative effects on [[Immunity (medical) | immunity]] and on species [[resilience (disambiguation) | resilience]].

==History==
{{Quote box
 |quote = We put down mad dogs; we kill the wild, untamed ox; we use the knife on sick sheep to stop their infecting the flock; we destroy abnormal offspring at birth; children, too, if they are born weak or deformed, we drown. Yet this is not the work of anger, but of reason – to separate the sound from the worthless.<ref>{{cite book |last=Seneca |first=Lucius Annaeus |authorlink=Seneca the Younger |year=1995 |title=Seneca: Moral and Political Essays |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xJmk6NzgawMC |location= |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page=32  |isbn=978-0-5213-4818-8 |accessdate=2 November 2013 }}</ref>
